## Page 1: What React Is and Where It Fits

React is a free, open‑source JavaScript library for building user interfaces on the web and in native apps.[web:154][web:157] It focuses on the **view layer**, meaning it helps you describe what the UI should look like for a given state, while leaving routing, data fetching, and backend concerns up to you or other libraries.[web:154][web:158] React applications are built from components—small, reusable pieces like buttons, forms, or entire sections of a page—that you compose together to create complex interfaces.[web:155][web:161] This component‑based approach makes it easier to reuse code, keep concerns separated, and reason about how changes in data affect what users see.[web:155][web:158]

In the modern frontend stack, React usually sits at the top of the UI layer, talking to APIs and backends over HTTP.[web:158][web:160] A typical setup might be: a React single‑page application (SPA) in the browser, a REST or GraphQL API on the server, and one or more external services such as authentication providers or AI APIs.[web:158][web:160] The React app is responsible for rendering views, handling user interactions, managing client‑side state, and calling those services when needed.[web:154][web:161] This makes React a natural fit when you want a responsive interface that feels more like an app and less like a set of static pages.[web:160][web:163]

React is declarative: instead of manually updating the DOM, you describe what the UI should look like for a given state, and React updates the DOM for you.[web:154][web:161] Under the hood, React uses a virtual DOM—an in‑memory representation of the UI—to calculate the minimal set of changes needed when state updates, which improves performance on complex pages.[web:155][web:158] You typically write React UI using JSX, a syntax that lets you embed HTML‑like tags directly inside JavaScript, so the structure of the UI and its behaviour can live together in the same component.[web:155][web:158] This combination of components, JSX, and the virtual DOM is what most developers mean when they talk about “building with React”.[web:155][web:158]

React doesn’t enforce a single way to structure your whole app, which is both a strength and a source of confusion. For small projects, you might use React with a simple bundler like Vite and manage state using hooks like `useState` and `useEffect`.[web:154][web:158] As projects grow, teams often add patterns and libraries for routing, global state, forms, UI components, and data fetching, or move to frameworks like Next.js that sit on top of React.[web:158][web:159] The important thing is to understand React’s role: it’s the UI engine that renders components and responds to state changes, not a full “all‑in‑one” framework.[web:154][web:157]

For AI‑powered frontends, React is useful because it makes it straightforward to wire user input, network calls, and UI updates together. The user types into a component (like a chat box or form), React holds that input in state, and then your code can call an AI API and render the response when it arrives.[web:145][web:146] You can keep the UI responsive by showing loading spinners, disabling buttons, and streaming responses into the interface as they come back from the API.[web:145] This document will focus on that pattern: React for the interactive UI and free or free‑tier AI APIs as the “brains” behind features like chat, summarisation, and content generation.[web:147][web:148]

---

## Page 2: React Project Setup and File Structure

For React in 2026, the simplest **fully free** setup is a Vite + React project, hosted on a free static host like GitHub Pages, Netlify, or Vercel’s free plan (no credit card for personal/public projects).[web:164][web:165][web:167][web:169] This stack gives you a fast dev server, modern bundling, and push‑to‑deploy hosting without paying for servers or managed runtimes.[web:164][web:166][web:169] You install Node.js once on your machine, generate a Vite+React app, and from there everything else—development, builds, and static hosting—can stay inside the free tier as long as your traffic and build minutes remain modest.[web:164][web:165][web:167]

A typical Vite + React project created with the official scaffolder has a small, predictable structure.[web:164][web:166][web:168] At the root you’ll see files like `index.html`, `package.json`, `vite.config.(js|ts)`, a lockfile, and config for tools like ESLint or TypeScript.[web:164][web:168][web:171] The `public/` folder holds static assets that are served as‑is (for example logos or static images), while `src/` contains your React code, starting from an entry file such as `main.jsx` or `main.tsx` and an `App` component.[web:164][web:166][web:171] When Vite builds the project, it turns this into static assets (HTML, JS, CSS) that you can drop onto any static hosting provider’s free plan.[web:164][web:167][web:169]

Inside `src/`, it’s common to split code into folders like `components/` for reusable UI pieces, `pages/` for top‑level screens, and `lib/` or `services/` for API helpers and utilities.[web:164][web:171] Your React entry file typically imports a root `<App />` component and renders it into a DOM node in `index.html`, often using `ReactDOM.createRoot` from React 18+.[web:154][web:161] From there you can grow the structure gradually: add `hooks/` for custom hooks, `context/` for context providers, and an `api/` or `ai/` folder for functions that call AI endpoints.[web:158][web:160] Keeping AI‑related code in one place makes it easier to swap between providers or move calls to a backend later without rewiring your whole app.[web:145][web:146]

For a fully free workflow, you want both code hosting and deployment to cost nothing. Using GitHub for source control and GitHub Pages, Netlify, or Vercel for static hosting covers that: all three support free hosting for small React/Vite apps, with automated builds on push.[web:165][web:167][web:169] GitHub Pages is ideal for simple static SPAs, while Netlify and Vercel offer more features like automatic previews and easy custom domains, all within generous free tiers as long as your project stays in personal/low‑traffic territory.[web:165][web:167][web:169] In this document we’ll assume you’re using Vite for local development and one of these free hosts for deployment, so you can focus on wiring React to AI APIs without paying for infrastructure.[web:164][web:165][web:167]

---

## Page 3: Core React Concepts for Frontend Work

At the heart of React frontend work are three ideas: components, props, and state. Components are just JavaScript functions that return JSX, which is an HTML‑like syntax embedded in JavaScript and compiled down to `React.createElement` calls.[web:176][web:178] You build your UI by composing small components (buttons, inputs, layout blocks) into larger ones (forms, pages) rather than manipulating the DOM directly.[web:155][web:176] Props (short for “properties”) are how data flows **into** a component from its parent; they are read‑only inputs used to configure how the component renders.[web:173][web:179] This one‑way data flow makes it easier to trace where a value comes from and how changes propagate through your UI.[web:175][web:179]

State is a component’s private, changeable data—its “memory” over time.[web:172][web:175] In function components you manage state with hooks like `useState`, which returns a state value and a setter function; when you call the setter, React re‑renders the component with the new state.[web:174][web:178][web:180] A common pattern is to keep “source of truth” state high enough in the tree (for example in a page or container component), and pass data down via props and callbacks back up to update that state.[web:175][web:179] Props are therefore external, immutable inputs, while state is internal, mutable data owned by the component that defines how it behaves and renders.[web:179][web:181]

Modern React leans heavily on hooks to handle state and side effects. `useState` is the basic state hook; `useEffect` lets you run side effects like data fetching, subscriptions, or timers in response to renders and dependency changes.[web:174][web:177][web:180] For example, you might use `useEffect` to call an AI API whenever a query string changes, then store the result in state and render it into the component.[web:175][web:177] Other hooks like `useRef` for mutable references and `useContext` for global-ish state help you avoid prop‑drilling and manage more complex screens without reaching for external state libraries immediately.[web:175][web:181] Together, function components + hooks cover most frontend needs, including AI calls, without extra paid tools or services.[web:175][web:180]

React’s rendering model is declarative: given some state and props, your component returns what the UI *should* look like, and React figures out how to update the actual DOM efficiently.[web:154][web:175] When either state or props change, React re‑runs the component function, compares the new virtual DOM tree to the previous one, and applies only the minimal changes to the real DOM.[web:173][web:176] This lets you write straightforward “data in → UI out” logic instead of manually attaching and removing DOM nodes, which is especially useful in AI‑driven interfaces where responses can be streamed or updated incrementally.[web:154][web:175] As long as you keep your components pure—no hidden mutations during render—and push all external effects into hooks, React remains predictable even as your frontend grows.[web:178][web:181]

---

## Page 4: State, Props, and Data Flow in React

React is built around a one‑way data flow: data lives in a “source of truth” and moves down the tree as props, while events move back up via callbacks.[web:184][web:190][web:191] The parent component owns state and passes pieces of it to children as read‑only props so they can render UI based on that data.[web:184][web:185] When something needs to change (a form field, a selected item, a toggle), the child calls a function provided by the parent, and the parent updates its state, triggering a re‑render with new props.[web:183][web:186][web:191] This pattern keeps a single writer for shared data and makes it easier to trace where changes come from.[web:187][web:190]

State is mutable data local to a component, created with hooks like `useState` in function components.[web:178][web:188] You use state for things that change over time in response to user actions, timers, or network results—current input values, loading flags, lists of AI responses, and so on.[web:177][web:188] Props, by contrast, are immutable inputs given to a component by its parent; the child is not allowed to change them directly and instead signals intent to change via callback props.[web:179][web:185][web:188] A simple rule of thumb is: if multiple components need to read or update the same data, the state for that data should live in their nearest common ancestor and be passed down as props.[web:183][web:186][web:189]

“Lifting state up” is the standard way to keep siblings or distant components in sync.[web:183][web:186][web:189] You identify state that is currently duplicated across components (for example, a query string in both a search box and a results panel), move that state into their closest shared parent, and then pass it down along with change handlers.[web:183][web:186] The parent becomes the single source of truth: children receive the current value via props and notify the parent of changes through callback props such as `onChange` or `onSelect`.[web:186][web:189] This is the core pattern you’ll use for AI UIs: keep the AI request/response state high in the tree and let lower‑level components render or tweak it without owning the core data themselves.[web:187][web:190]

Unidirectional data flow has a few important benefits for real projects. It makes component behaviour more predictable because data always travels in the same direction—down via props, up via events—and there is a single owner for any given piece of state.[web:184][web:187][web:191] Debugging is easier because you can inspect a component’s props and state at a point in time and know exactly what the UI should be for that combination.[web:184][web:188][web:190] It also works well with React’s rendering and reconciliation model: when the source‑of‑truth state changes, React re‑renders the relevant subtree, calculates the minimal DOM changes, and updates the view.[web:178][web:190][web:191] For AI‑driven frontends, this means you can treat “AI output” as just another piece of state flowing through a predictable pipeline—fetch, store, render—without needing paid state‑management tooling or complex bi‑directional bindings.[web:175][web:188][web:191]

