## Page 5: Calling AI APIs Safely from React

Calling AI APIs from React is technically just HTTP requests, but you have to treat security and cost limits seriously, especially if you want to stay fully free. The main rule is simple: never put private API keys directly in the browser bundle where anyone can view them. Instead, you either use providers that expose key‑less public endpoints for low‑risk use, or you put a tiny (still-free) backend or serverless function in front of the AI API and keep the real key there. In both cases, your React code only ever talks to URLs you’re comfortable exposing to users.

For free‑first projects, prefer AI services that offer anonymous or key‑less usage, or demo endpoints with strict rate limits. Some free AI endpoints allow requests without authentication or with a public, non-sensitive token that you can rotate easily. Others provide browser‑friendly SDKs that are explicitly designed to run client‑side with limited capabilities and rate caps. These options are safer to call directly from React because you are not leaking any long‑lived secret. Where you must use a private key (for example, a standard text‑generation API), put that key in environment variables on a free backend (like a simple Node server, or serverless functions on Netlify/Vercel) and let React talk only to that backend.

On the React side, treat AI calls as just another async data‑fetching problem. Keep request input, loading flags, and responses in state, and centralise the actual `fetch`/`axios` logic in a small `api/aiClient.ts` (or similar) module so the rest of the app doesn’t need to know details about providers. Handle three core UI states explicitly: idle (no request yet), loading (in-flight), and done (success or error). Show a spinner or disabled button while waiting, render the AI response when it arrives, and show a clear error message when something fails instead of silently doing nothing. This keeps the UI responsive and makes rate limits or temporary failures much less painful for users.

You also need to defend both users and your free quotas. Validate and trim inputs before sending them to an AI API so users can’t accidentally (or deliberately) send huge prompts that burn through rate limits in one go. Debounce or throttle repeated calls from text inputs, and apply simple client‑side rate‑limiting like “ignore new calls if one is already in progress” or “cap to N calls per minute per user session”. Cache responses locally in memory or `localStorage` when it makes sense (for example, for the same prompt) so you don’t keep re‑using free‑tier calls for identical work. Combined, these patterns let you ship AI features in React that are cheap, predictable, and don’t leak secrets, while staying within the constraints of free and free‑tier services.


---

## Page 6: Using Free and Free-Tier AI Providers

When you’re building a React frontend and want AI “for free”, there are two main categories to care about: **truly free / key‑less options** and **free‑tier APIs that still need a key but cost nothing at small scale**.[web:148][web:204] Truly free options are the easiest to plug straight into React because you don’t have to protect secrets; they either expose open endpoints or run locally on your own hardware.[web:148][web:204] Free‑tier APIs usually give you a generous quota at zero cost but still require API keys and, in some cases, an account, so they’re better called from a tiny backend than directly from the browser.[web:148][web:204][web:205]

On the **fully free** side, you have things like Pollinations.ai, which lets you generate text and images through simple URLs or HTTP calls without an account or key.[web:204] That makes it ideal for experiments, portfolio projects, or teaching: you can call the API directly from React, show a loader while it responds, and never worry about leaked credentials.[web:204] Local tools such as Ollama also belong in this bucket: they run models on your own machine and expose a local HTTP API, effectively giving you “unlimited” calls bounded only by your hardware.[web:148] For local‑only tools, your React app usually talks to `http://localhost:PORT` during development, and you treat the local AI process like any other backend.[web:148]

Free‑tier providers tend to offer more powerful models and better reliability, at the cost of setup and quotas. Hugging Face’s Inference API, for example, gives access to a huge catalog of open models for NLP, vision, and code with a free tier that doesn’t require a credit card but does enforce moderate rate limits.[web:148][web:150] Google’s Gemini API (via AI Studio) and similar offerings provide very capable text and multimodal models with daily or per‑minute quotas sufficient for small apps and prototypes.[web:148][web:202][web:204] Aggregator APIs like OpenRouter or multi‑model platforms can also offer free credits or limited daily usage across several high‑end models, which is useful when you want to compare outputs before committing to one provider.[web:148][web:204][web:203]

For a React developer, the strategy is to **start with the most free, least risky option** that fits your use case. If you just need simple text or image generation to prove a concept, a key‑less or local provider avoids the whole problem of secret management and billing.[web:148][web:204] When you need better quality or specific features, step up to a free‑tier API but call it through a minimal backend or serverless function, keeping your key on the server and your React code dumb: it only knows about your own endpoint.[web:148][web:205] In all cases, design your UI and state around limits: show clear errors when quotas are hit, keep prompts short by default, and cache results when possible so you don’t burn free calls on the same request over and over.[web:148][web:170][web:207]

---

## Page 7: Building a Simple AI-Powered React UI

The simplest useful AI UI you can build in React is a single-page “ask a question, get an answer” interface. You need four pieces of state: the current input text, a list of past messages or responses, a loading flag, and an error string. The core flow is: user types a prompt, clicks a button, you set loading to true, call a free or key‑less AI endpoint, store the response in state, and render it underneath the input. Keeping everything in one component at first makes it easier to see the full data flow before you start extracting smaller components.

A minimal component might have an input box, a “Ask AI” button, and a scrollable list of responses. When the form submits, you validate the input (non‑empty, length limit), set `loading = true`, clear any previous error, and send a `fetch` request to your chosen AI endpoint. Once the response arrives, you parse the JSON, append a new entry to a `messages` array in state (for example `{ role: 'user', text: prompt }` followed by `{ role: 'ai', text: answer }`), and set `loading = false`. If the request fails or the API returns an error, you set an error message in state and show it above or below the input instead of silently failing.

When you wire this into React, small UX details make a big difference. Disable the submit button while `loading` is true to prevent spamming the free API and to keep your UI predictable. Show a simple “Thinking…” spinner or skeleton while waiting so users know something is happening. Trim whitespace from prompts and, if you’re on a tight free tier, enforce a maximum character count and display how many characters the user has typed. If you want to feel a bit more “chat‑like”, render user and AI bubbles with different background colours and alignments, but keep the logic exactly the same: it’s just rendering the `messages` state array as a list.

To stay in the “free as long as possible” zone, you should also add a couple of guardrails to this simple UI. Track how many requests have been made in the current session (for example, with a simple counter in state) and soft‑limit it—once a user has made, say, 20 calls, show a message explaining that they’ve hit the demo limit and ask them to come back later. Avoid firing automatic calls on every keystroke; use an explicit “Send” or “Ask” button so you only call the AI when the user really wants to. These small constraints, combined with the React patterns you’ve already seen (state, props, and one‑way data flow), give you a robust, portfolio‑ready AI UI without paying for infrastructure or blowing through free API allowances.

---

## Page 8: Handling Errors, Rate Limits, and Loading States

When your React app talks to AI APIs, failures are guaranteed: network glitches, quota limits, malformed inputs, or provider outages. You want to design your UI and state so those failures are expected, visible, and recoverable instead of surprising.[web:218][web:219][web:222] At minimum, every AI call should track three bits of state: `isLoading`, `error`, and the last `result`. That lets you show different UI for “idle”, “loading”, “success”, and “error” without throwing exceptions or leaving the user staring at a frozen screen.[web:218][web:222] Wrap your request logic in `try/catch`, set `isLoading = true` before the call and `false` in `finally`, and always set an appropriate `error` message when something goes wrong.[web:218][web:220]

For free and free‑tier AI providers, rate limits are one of the most common failure modes. APIs will often respond with HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests) or include headers that describe how many requests remain and when you can try again.[web:204][web:205] In your React UI, you should detect rate‑limit responses and show a specific message such as “You’ve hit the free limit, try again in a few minutes” rather than a generic “Something went wrong”.[web:218][web:222] On the client side, add lightweight throttling: block multiple concurrent requests from the same button, debounce inputs that could trigger repeated calls, and track how many calls have been made in the current session so you can enforce a soft limit before the provider does.[web:170][web:207]

Loading states are where most AI UIs either feel smooth or painful. Instead of leaving the button active and the page static, disable actions while a request is in flight and show a clear indicator such as a spinner, skeleton UI, or “Thinking…” label.[web:218][web:222][web:227] For longer operations, break the process into steps and show progress text (“Sending request…”, “Waiting for AI…”, “Formatting answer…”) so users know the app is alive, even if the provider is slow.[web:227] When an error occurs, keep the user’s input visible, preserve the previous responses, and offer a “Retry” button that reuses the same prompt, so they don’t feel punished for issues outside their control.[web:218][web:220] Thinking in terms of explicit loading, error, and success states—rather than “fire and forget”—makes your AI frontend feel robust even when you are leaning heavily on fragile free tiers.[web:218][web:219][web:222]

---

## Page 9: Deploying a React + AI Frontend for Free

Deploying a React + AI frontend for free usually means serving a static React build on a free host and, if you need private API keys, hiding them behind a tiny free backend. For pure key‑less or local AI setups, you can keep it completely static: run `npm run build` (or the Vite equivalent) to produce an optimised `dist/` folder, then upload that folder to a free static hosting service like Netlify, Vercel, GitHub Pages, or Cloudflare Pages. These platforms all have free tiers suitable for personal or low‑traffic projects and can connect directly to your Git repository so each push triggers a new build and deployment.[web:165][web:228][web:231]

The basic “static only” deployment flow looks like this: push your React code to a Git repository, connect the repo to your chosen host, select your build command and output folder, and let the platform handle builds on every push. For Vite projects, this usually means a build command of `npm run build` and an output directory of `dist/`; for Create React App, it’s `npm run build` and `build/`. On Netlify or Vercel you can do this entirely through their web UI: sign up, import your repo, configure build settings, and get a live URL within a few minutes.[web:165][web:228][web:233][web:234] GitHub Pages and Cloudflare Pages offer similar flows for static assets, with slightly more manual configuration for branches and build settings.[web:228]

If your AI provider requires a secret key, you’ll usually add a minimal backend while still staying fully within free tiers. One common pattern is to create a single serverless function (for example, on Netlify Functions or Vercel Serverless) that accepts requests from your React app, adds the AI API key from environment variables, forwards the request to the AI provider, and returns the result. Your frontend then calls only this function’s URL, never the real AI endpoint, so no secrets are exposed in the browser. Even with this extra hop, everything can remain free for small workloads because the major frontend hosts include a modest amount of serverless function time in their free plans.

To keep your free deployment sustainable, you also need a bit of operational discipline. Keep bundle sizes sensible so you don’t waste visitors’ bandwidth and your own build resources. Log and handle AI errors gracefully instead of leaving the UI blank, and consider simple client‑side limits like capping the number of requests per session so you don’t accidentally hit backend or AI provider quotas. If your usage grows, you can later migrate the same React code to a paid plan or a more robust backend without rewriting the UI. For portfolio projects, prototypes, and small internal tools, though, a static React build plus free hosting and carefully chosen AI providers is enough to get a real AI‑powered app live on the public internet without paying a single penny.


---

## Page 10: Finishing Page

By now you’ve seen the full path from “plain React app” to “deployed AI‑powered frontend that costs nothing to run at small scale”. You start with a simple Vite + React project, keep components, state, and props under control, and treat AI APIs as just another async data source wired into your UI. The key is staying disciplined about one‑way data flow and keeping your AI integration isolated in a small client module or backend proxy so you can swap providers or move off free tiers later without rewriting everything.

If your priority is **fully free**, the stack looks like this: Vite + React, static hosting on Netlify/Vercel/GitHub Pages, and either a key‑less AI endpoint or a local AI server running on your own machine. As your needs grow, you can step up to free‑tier AI providers that require keys, hide those keys behind a tiny free backend, and keep the React app talking only to your own endpoint. Throughout, you manage loading, errors, and rate limits explicitly in state so the UI feels solid even when the underlying AI service is flaky or throttled.

A simple “next steps” checklist for this topic looks like:
- Build one minimal Q&A UI that talks to a fully free AI endpoint.
- Refactor AI calls into a dedicated `aiClient` module and add proper loading/error handling.
- Deploy the app to a free static host and test from a phone and a friend’s laptop.
- Only after that, experiment with more advanced models, streaming, or multi‑provider setups.

Treat this as a base pattern you can reuse: React on the front, the cheapest possible AI behind it, and a careful balance between “cool features” and “doesn’t secretly cost me money every month”.

